<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1919-02-12T08:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1919-02-12T08:00:00-05:00" n="802" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d802">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">867.48/1175: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Davis</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1919-02-12T13:00:00+00:00"><hi rend="italic">February 12,
                                        1919, 1 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[<hi rend="italic">Received
                                    1.12 p.m.</hi>]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>891. Your 496 [<hi rend="italic">4095</hi>], January 16 and your 4357
                                [<hi rend="italic">4367</hi>] February 3.<note n="16" xml:id="d802fn16">Latter not printed.</note> Foreign Office informs
                            me today that British Commander-in-Chief in the Mediterranean was
                            informed on the 18th January of the impending visit of the American
                            Relief Mission which would be followed by the three relief ships in
                            question and instructed to afford to the mission all practicable
                            facilities. They feel therefore that the three vessels will encounter no
                            obstacle on their arrival.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Davis</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>